Docker Debugging & Log Analysis

Docker debugging is the process of identifying and fixing issues in Docker containers, images, networks, or applications. Most issues can be diagnosed using Docker's built-in commands.

Docker Debugging Workflow
Container Problem
       │
       ▼
Check Container Status
       │
       ▼
Check Logs
       │
       ▼
Inspect Container
       │
       ▼
Login into Container
       │
       ▼
Check Network
       │
       ▼
Check Volumes
       │
       ▼
Check CPU/Memory
       │
       ▼
Fix the Problem
1. Check Container Status

First check whether the container is running.

docker ps

Output

CONTAINER ID   IMAGE    STATUS
123abc         nginx    Up 5 minutes

If you don't see your container:

docker ps -a

Output

CONTAINER ID   IMAGE    STATUS
123abc         nginx    Exited (1)
What to check?
Running
Exited
Restarting
Created
Paused

If the container is Exited, check the logs.

2. Analyze Container Logs

Logs are the first place to look when an application fails.

Show logs

docker logs nginx

Example

Starting Nginx...

Error: Port already in use

Follow logs continuously

docker logs -f nginx

Show last 20 lines

docker logs --tail 20 nginx

Show timestamps

docker logs -t nginx
Common log messages

Port conflict

Bind for 0.0.0.0:80 failed

Another process is already using port 80.

Database connection

Connection refused

Database container may not be running or reachable.

File not found

No such file or directory

Incorrect path or missing file.

3. Inspect Container
docker inspect nginx

Shows

IP Address
Mounts
Volumes
Environment Variables
Restart Policy
Network
Ports

Example

IPAddress:
172.17.0.2

RestartPolicy:
always

Get only the IP

docker inspect -f '{{.NetworkSettings.IPAddress}}' nginx
4. Login into Container

Open shell

docker exec -it nginx bash

If bash isn't installed

docker exec -it nginx sh

Inside container

pwd

ls

cat /etc/os-release

ps -ef

Useful for checking:

Files
Configuration
Installed packages
Running processes
5. Check Running Processes
docker top nginx

Output

PID USER COMMAND

12 root nginx

18 root nginx worker

Shows processes running inside the container.

6. Monitor CPU and Memory
docker stats

Output

NAME      CPU %   MEM

nginx      2.3%   25MB

mysql      85%    900MB

Use this when:

Container is slow
High memory usage
CPU spikes
7. Check Port Mapping
docker port nginx

Output

80/tcp -> 0.0.0.0:8080

Means

Host:8080
      │
Container:80

If users cannot access the application, verify the expected port mapping exists.

8. Check Network

List networks

docker network ls

Inspect

docker network inspect bridge

Check communication

docker exec app ping mysql

If ping fails

Containers may be on different networks.
Wrong container/service name.
Network configuration issue.
9. Check Mounted Volumes
docker inspect mysql

Look for

Mounts

Example

Source

/var/lib/docker/volumes/mysql-data

Destination

/var/lib/mysql

If no volume is mounted, database data will be lost when the container is removed.

10. Check Docker Events
docker events

Output

Container start

Container stop

Container die

Useful for troubleshooting unexpected restarts or crashes.

11. Check Disk Usage
docker system df

Output

Images

Containers

Volumes

Build Cache

Shows how much storage Docker is using.

12. Copy Files for Analysis

Copy from container

docker cp nginx:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf .

Copy into container

docker cp nginx.conf nginx:/etc/nginx/

Useful when reviewing or replacing configuration files.

13. Check File Changes
docker diff nginx

Output

A /tmp/test.txt

C /etc/nginx/nginx.conf

Meaning:

A = Added
C = Changed
D = Deleted
Common Debugging Scenarios
Scenario 1: Container Exits Immediately

Check status

docker ps -a

Output

Exited (1)

Check logs

docker logs app

Output

Database connection failed

Cause: Application cannot connect to the database.

Solution: Verify the database container is running, networking is correct, and connection settings are valid.

Scenario 2: Website Not Opening

Check

docker ps

Check ports

docker port nginx

Output

80 -> 8080

Verify:

Container is running.
Correct port is mapped.
Application inside the container is listening on the expected port.
Scenario 3: Container Restarting Continuously
docker ps

Output

Restarting (1)

Check logs

docker logs nginx

Example

Configuration syntax error

Fix the configuration and restart the container.

Scenario 4: Two Containers Cannot Communicate

Test connectivity

docker exec frontend ping backend

If it fails

docker network inspect app-network

Verify both containers are attached to the same network.

Scenario 5: High CPU Usage
docker stats

Output

CPU

98%

Investigate the running processes:

docker top app

Then inspect the application logs to identify excessive work or loops.

Scenario 6: Database Data Lost

Check

docker inspect mysql

Look for

Mounts

If no Docker volume is configured, the database files were stored only in the container's writable layer and were removed with the container.

Important Debugging Commands
Command	Purpose
docker ps	Running containers
docker ps -a	All containers
docker logs <container>	View logs
docker logs -f <container>	Live logs
docker logs --tail 50 <container>	Last 50 log lines
docker inspect <container>	Container details
docker exec -it <container> bash	Open shell
docker top <container>	Running processes
docker stats	CPU & memory usage
docker port <container>	Port mappings
docker network ls	List networks
docker network inspect <network>	Network details
docker volume ls	List volumes
docker diff <container>	File changes
docker cp	Copy files to/from container
docker events	Docker events
docker system df	Disk usage
docker system prune	Remove unused resources
Real-Time Example

Suppose your application is not working.

Step 1: Check if it's running
docker ps -a

Output:

STATUS: Exited (1)
Step 2: Read the logs
docker logs myapp

Output:

Error: Cannot connect to MySQL
Step 3: Verify the database
docker ps

If MySQL isn't running:

docker start mysql
Step 4: Test connectivity
docker exec myapp ping mysql

If successful:

64 bytes from mysql
Step 5: Restart the application
docker restart myapp
Step 6: Confirm it's healthy
docker ps
docker logs myapp

If the logs show normal startup and the container remains in the Up state, the issue has been resolved.

Interview Questions
1. How do you troubleshoot a container that exits immediately?
docker ps -a
docker logs <container>
docker inspect <container>
docker exec (if it stays running long enough)
Verify image, environment variables, volumes, and networking.
2. How do you monitor container resource usage?
docker stats
3. How do you access a running container?
docker exec -it <container> bash
4. How do you view application logs?
docker logs -f <container>
5. How do you verify network connectivity?
docker network inspect <network>
docker exec <container> ping <service>
